## Computed Boundary

& [Boundary_001_PowerExponentParity] is structural
  + [statement] is 641^N is odd for every listed odd Fermat-prime N
  + [meaning] is plus-one remains factor-forced and parity switching does not create even-exponent behavior in this branch

& [Boundary_002_Mod3Obstruction] is decisive_for_r0_and_r2
  + [statement] is 65537 is congruent to 2 modulo 3 and 641^N is odd, so 65537^(641^N) is congruent to -1 modulo 3
  + [r_0] is shift 2^0 = 1, so -1 + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo 3
  + [r_2] is shift 2^2 = 4, so -1 + 4 is congruent to 0 modulo 3
  + [result] is +1 and +4 levels are obstructed for every listed N

& [Boundary_003_Mod7Obstruction] is decisive_for_r1
  + [statement] is 65537 is congruent to 3 modulo 7 and 641 is congruent to 4 modulo 7
  + [exponent_mod] is 641^N is congruent to 5 modulo 6 for the listed odd N
  + [result] is 65537^(641^N) + 2 is divisible by 7 for every listed N
  + [meaning] is the +2 level collapses under the power-exponent branch

& [Conclusion_001] is abandon_as_wrong_identity
  + [statement] is the 641^N branch does not track the intended identity
  + [reason] is more than two defining set members fail; in fact every tested member is obstructed at the tested levels
  + [abandonment_rule] is C:\Project\Pinky\RiemannHypothesis\analysis\prime_periphery\2026-06-26_identity_tracking_abandonment_rule.sop
  + [preserved_meaning] is this branch explains a residue obstruction pattern, not a candidate Fermat-coherent prime sequence
